interesting and useful things you can do for infosec work with Python¶

programming not required to get started¶

aka: "infosec python ideas" talk

What / why¶

  • Automation and empowerment
    • Computers are machines that run code
      • Read code to understand what computers do
      • Write code to change what computers do
    • Do more and better things, reduce drudgery and slogging at $work and in life
    • Share what you know
  • Python and Infosec
    • easy to learn (as programming languages go)
    • "batteries included" and many libraries available
    • used in many infosec tools by everyone (.* hats)
      • many great tools written in or extensible in Python

  • this talk

    • lots of people want to learn more about, start using Python
      • their goals and interests, skill levels vary
    • many people struggle with finding an interesting tool or project to practice on
      • or just a goal to aim at
    • thus "interesting and useful things you can do for infosec work with Python"
      • and "programming not required to get started" <= needs more stars

  • BETA Talk disclaimer

    • Feedback appreciated: here, Discord, email, etc
  • me ?

    • security architect somewhere important
    • community instructor / life-long student
    • might not be a cat on the keyboard

demo¶

  • get a (better) terminal session
    • python3 -c "import pty;pty.spawn('/bin/whoami')"
  • upload and download files over http and and other means
    • python3 -m http.server || python2.7 -m SimpleHTTPServer || socket.Socket
  • exploit vulnerabilities
    • python -c "print('{}'.format('A' * 1024))"
  • notebooks: code, results, documentation together
    • also, slides:
      • https://towardsdatascience.com/5-slides-for-tips-on-presentation-mode-in-jupyter-notebook-f858b15fff4f?gi=cd220161b46b
      • https://nbconvert.readthedocs.io/en/latest/usage.html#reveal-js-html-slideshow
  • automate & extend security tools:
    • Ghidra eg: https://github.com/ghidraninja/ghidra_scripts

WannaCry sample from https://bazaar.abuse.ch/download/07c44729e2c570b37db695323249474831f5861d45318bf49ccf5d2f5c8ea1cd/

Initial strings analysis turned up some interesting leads, simple Ghidra Python to mark one for followup.

00431330 %s -m security "%s -m security" ds

interesting_addr= toAddr("00431330")
listing = currentProgram.getListing()
codeUnit = listing.getCodeUnitAt(interesting_addr)
codeUnit.setComment(codeUnit.PRE_COMMENT, "This is an interesting string!")

wave at¶

  • contribute bugs, code, documentation, and tests to projects
  • upload and download files over http(s) and and other means
    • http.server, requests
    • hit an API and get stuff, like from VT: https://developers.virustotal.com/reference/overview
  • Program electronic devices to do your bidding!
    • Try CircuitPython
  • capture, analyse, and manipulate packets
    • scapy: https://scapy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/
  • do simple or complex data analysis, and make charts and graphs
    • Jupyter, Pandas : https://infosecjupyterthon.com/introduction.html
  • automate & extend security tools:
    • Ghidra eg: https://github.com/ghidraninja/ghidra_scripts
    • Burp Suite https://portswigger.net/burp/documentation/desktop/tools/extender , ZAP https://github.com/zaproxy/zap-api-python
    • Metasploit Framework https://github.com/rapid7/metasploit-framework/blob/master/modules/auxiliary/example.py etc.
    • Empire: https://bc-security.gitbook.io/empire-wiki/module-development/python-modules
  • (advanced) integrate tools and glue systems together
  • (advanced) make entirely new tools
